Bitwise XOR (^) Operator
Full form: Exclusive OR

Rule:

Copy
Edit
1 ^ 1 = 0
0 ^ 0 = 0
1 ^ 0 = 1
0 ^ 1 = 1
Meaning: Result is 1 if bits are different, else 0.

Why use XOR?
Swapping values without a temporary variable.
Finding a single unique element in an array where all others are duplicate.
Simple encryption and decryption.\



| a   | b   | a(binary) | b(binary) | a ^ b (binary) | Result |
| --- | --- | --------- | --------- | -------------- | ------ |
| 5   | 3   | 0101      | 0011      | 0110           | 6      |
| 4   | 4   | 0100      | 0100      | 0000           | 0      |
| 8   | 2   | 1000      | 0010      | 1010           | 10     |
| 7   | 1   | 0111      | 0001      | 0110           | 6      |
| 12  | 5   | 1100      | 0101      | 1001           | 9      |
| 15  | 0   | 1111      | 0000      | 1111           | 15     |
| 6   | 9   | 0110      | 1001      | 1111           | 15     |
| 1   | 1   | 0001      | 0001      | 0000           | 0      |
| 2   | 3   | 0010      | 0011      | 0001           | 1      |
| 10  | 5   | 1010      | 0101      | 1111           | 15     |
| 20  | 25  | 10100     | 11001     | 01101          | 13     |
| 50  | 30  | 110010    | 11110     | 101100         | 44     |
| 100 | 200 | 1100100   | 11001000  | 10101100       | 172    |
| 255 | 1   | 11111111  | 00000001  | 11111110       | 254    |
